h3. Issue Summary
Using the Jira issues calendar gadget with a query that contains the *project category* field, will not return only issues from projects on that category.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create a project P1;
 # Create a project category. Example: Cat 1;
 # In that project, create a version and assign some issues to it;
 # Follow the same steps above for a different project P2 which doesn't belong to the same category;
 # Create a filter query similar to:
 #* {code:SQL}category = "Cat 1"{code}
 #* Save the filter;
 # Create a dashboard and include the Jira issues calendar gadget;
 # Include the saved filter above and save it;

h3. Expected Results
Only issues from the projects in the category mentioned on the filter will return.

h3. Actual Results
Issues from projects different from the category set on the filter will also return.

h3. Workaround
Currently, there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available.

For efficient use of the administrative use of Jira, it's essential to have the capability of restricting the use of this button. Also, this would be important for users who don't want to adopt the new issue view. Some examples below:
* Custom fields on the top of the page;
* Which fields are populated by the user;
* Which fields ate filled by automation;
* Fields to not being editable but visible by specific groups of users;
* Scroll to find relevant fields;
